## Migration Analysis

**Patterns identified:**

| Location | Pattern | API |
|----------|---------|-----|
| `ProcessLoop` | Cancellable work loop | `while (_running)` + `Thread.Abort` |
| `ProcessLoop` catch | ThreadAbortException as control flow | Rollback on abort |
| `ProcessLoop` catch | ResetAbort to continue | `Thread.ResetAbort()` |
| `Stop()` | Force-kill after timeout | `_workerThread.Abort()` |

All four are replaced by **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested â€” clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Abort
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread did not exit in time â€” log a warning.
            // In cooperative cancellation, you cannot force-kill it.
            // See pitfalls below.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `ThreadAbortException` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No auto-rethrow with `OperationCanceledException`; just exit the loop |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of preemptive kill |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Join actually waits for the thread; Sleep just delays then aborts blindly |

---

## Critical: You Must Update `GetNextItem`

The comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." **This is the most important part.** If it blocks forever, cancellation never takes effect because cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints.

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks indefinitely, ignores cancellation
private Item GetNextItem() {
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks forever if queue is empty
}

// AFTER: pass the token so blocking unblocks on cancel
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) {
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitHandle.WaitOne`, or socket I/O:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollIntervalMs);

// Replace WaitHandle.WaitOne with cancellable version
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { myEvent, token.WaitHandle });
```

---

## Common Pitfalls for This Code

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---|---|
| **Not passing `token` to `GetNextItem`** | Thread stays blocked forever after `Cancel()` â€” `Stop()` hangs or times out |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers/callbacks. Implement `IDisposable` (shown above) |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter to avoid swallowing unrelated cancellations |
| **Expecting `Cancel()` to be instant** | Cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running |
| **No fallback when `Join` times out** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, there is **no force-kill** in .NET 8. If the thread won't cooperate, your only option is `Process.Kill` on a child process. Design `GetNextItem`/`ProcessItem` to always respect the token |

